communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above cited reference "AQIS (1999)" includes article 2.3.17 "Swine
influenza virus". Under "Transmission via semen" (page 30), it says:
"Transmission of swine influenza is via inhalation of aerosols. Swine
influenza virus does not produce viraemia. The virus is not found outside
the respiratory tract and associated lymph nodes (1). The virus has not
been recovered from semen. Hare (2) notes that this virus could be present
in semen but the disease probably would not be transmitted through
artificial insemination.

References
----------
1. Bachmann PA. Swine influenza virus. In: Pensaert MB, editor. Virus
infections of vertebrates, 2 - virus infections of porcines. Amsterdam:
Elsevier, 1989: 193-207.
2. Hare, WCD. Diseases transmissible by semen and embryo transfer
techniques. Technical Series 4. Paris: OIE, 1985.

Though animal influenza viruses do occasionally cause viraemia (such as
HPAI H5N1 in cats; see Giese, Harder, Teifke, et al. The role of T cells in
avian influenza H5N1 infected cats. Veterinary Immunology and
Immunopathology 2009; 128: 343), it appears that viraemia generally does
not occur in cases of (classical) swine influenza. The results of the
further experimental studies on the epidemiology of the novel influenza A
(H1N1) virus in various animal species, reportedly to be performed soon by
the Avian Influenza Community Reference Laboratory at VLA, Weybridge, UK
together with other European laboratories, are anticipated with great
interest. It is to be hoped that these studies will address also the
viraemia issue, relevant to the safety of pork. - Mod.AS]
